Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

  • Certain columns, like ‘cast’ and ‘genres’, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters.

  • There are some odd characters in the ‘cast’ column. Don’t worry about cleaning them. You can leave them as is.

  • The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

df.drop(columns=['homepage','tagline','overview','imdb_id'], inplace=True)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Research Question 1: Who are the most famous actors?¶

In [15]:
# Split the cast column into separate columns
df = df.join(df['cast'].str.split('|', expand=True).add_prefix('cast_'))

# Melt the cast columns into rows
df = pd.melt(df, id_vars=['original_title'], value_vars=['cast_0', 'cast_1', 'cast_2', 'cast_3', 'cast_4'], value_name='actor').dropna()

# Group by actor and count the number of movies in each group
actor_counts = df.groupby('actor').size().reset_index(name='count')

# Sort the actors by count in descending order
actor_counts = actor_counts.sort_values('count', ascending=False)

# Display the top 10 actors
print(actor_counts.head(10))

Research Question 3: What are the most popular genres over time? Have audience preferences changed?¶

In [ ]:
# Converting release_date to datetime format
df['release_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['release_date'])
In [16]:
# Splitting genres column into separate genre columns
df = pd.concat([df, df['genres'].str.split('|', expand=True)], axis=1)

# Unpivot genre columns into rows
df = pd.melt(df, id_vars=['release_year'], value_vars=[0,1,2,3,4], value_name='genre').dropna()

# Grouping by release_year and genre, and count the number of movies in each group
genre_counts = df.groupby(['release_year', 'genre']).size().reset_index(name='count')

# Pivot the data to have the genres as columns and the release_year as index
genre_counts_pivot = genre_counts.pivot(index='release_year', columns='genre', values='count')

# Defining a custom color palette with 20 colors
custom_palette = sns.color_palette("husl", 20)

# Creating a line plot using pandas
ax = genre_counts_pivot.plot(kind='line', figsize=(15,15), color=custom_palette)

# Set the plot title and axis labels
ax.set_title('Popularity of Genres Over Time')
ax.set_xlabel('Release Year')
ax.set_ylabel('Number of Movies')

# Finding the 5th highest count for the last year
last_year = genre_counts_pivot.index[-1]
top_genres = genre_counts_pivot.loc[last_year].sort_values(ascending=False)
fifth_highest_count = top_genres.iloc[4]

# Adding text labels to the plot for the top genres in the last year
for genre in top_genres.index:
    count = genre_counts_pivot.loc[last_year, genre]
    if count >= fifth_highest_count:
        ax.text(last_year, count, genre, ha='left', va='center')

# Showing the plot
plt.show()



###The graph shows that Drama, followed by comedy, thriller, action and adventure are the genders most watched nowadays.
###You can see there's changes of the most popular genre accordint to the year
###Audience preference has changed

Research Question 5: Is there a relationship between budget and revenue_adj?¶

In [10]:
# Converting the 'revenue_adj' and 'budget' columns to numeric data types
df['revenue_adj'] = pd.to_numeric(df['revenue_adj'], errors='coerce')
df['budget'] = pd.to_numeric(df['budget'], errors='coerce')

# Dropping rows with null values in the 'revenue_adj' and 'budget' columns
df = df.dropna(subset=['revenue_adj', 'budget'])

#scatter plot of 'budget' vs 'revenue_adj'
plt.scatter(df['budget'], df['revenue_adj'])
plt.xlabel('Budget')
plt.ylabel('Revenue (Adjusted)')
plt.title('Relationship between Budget and Adjusted Revenue')
plt.show()

#budget has a higher correlation with revenue adj compared to the popularity of the movies

Conclusions¶

Although our dataset has more than 10,000 rows it's insufficient to draw precise conclusions because:

  1. Majority of the data columns are irrelevant for the analysis

  2. There's a lot of NaN values. A possible solution would be re-do a web scrapping for a better data quality or prepare data from a different source than the one we have.

  3. As seen in the revenue and budget variables, there's a lot of 0-valued data, and after the cleaning step the data gets really small and possibly not representative.

  4. Besides poor data quality, one concern part would be that the data is outdated for the main variables, it should include at least streaming services.

Conclusions from the analysis performed:¶

  1. The most famous actor is Robert de Nirto with 52 original movies.
  2. Revenuew, budget and popularity have moderate to high correlation. Bein budget and revenue the most positivly correlated.
  3. Drama, followed by comedy, thriller, action and adventure are the genders most watched nowadays. There's changes of the most popular genre accordint to the year, and audience preference has changed as well.
  4. Budget has a higher correlation with revenue adj compared to the popularity of the movies.
